entry.title: Broaden ownership of safe_browsing feature files
entry.content:
features.h and features.cc are a central repository for base::Features

used by safe_browsing code, but right now these files are only owned

by the top-level safe_browsing OWNERS in

//components/safe_browsing/OWNERS. This leads to code reviews where

the implementation change is fully reviewed by a more scoped owner,

but the flag definition needs another reviewer. This CL broadens

ownership of these two files to avoid needing a second reviewer.

entry.title: [TLDD] Fix for drop onto compositorViewHolder.
entry.content:
Dropping onto web content was working before and stopped since CL [1] landed. We were not using text/* mimetype before but added this in the below CL to support drag to open new instance of Chrome. Since EventForwarder relies on this mimetype, it was catching the dragevents and returning true. They were not getting passed on to CVH drag listener [2].

entry.title: [Downloads] AddWarningActionEvent for SHOWN on chrome://downloads
entry.content:
Previously we only logged a SHOWN event to DownloadItemWarningData if

the warning was shown in the download bubble. This can miss some cases

because the download bubble is suppressed for 15s after it is shown, so

it is possible for a dangerous download warning to occur but not be

shown in the download bubble. Later on, the user could go to

chrome://downloads and be shown the warning, but no

DownloadItemWarningData events would be logged due to the absence of the

initial SHOWN.



This fixes that by adding a SHOWN event from chrome://downloads as well.

The logic in DownloadItemWarningData prevents double-logging.

entry.title: Webview suppress tap during fling
entry.content:
For apps that disables fling in webview by not calling computeScroll,

webview still internally has a fling curve that's just not ticked. This

caused crbug.com/514783 for those apps because tap during fling cancels

the fling instead of registering as a tap. The old fix was to turn off

this tap suppression during fling entirely, which causes this current

bug where apps that allow normal fling will have tap register as a tap,

which differs from chrome behavior.



This changes so that fling is cancelled entirely for apps that do not

call computeScroll, but keeps tap suppression behavior.

entry.title: [Downloads] Consolidate and fix Download.ShowedDownloadWarning logging
entry.content:
Previously we only logged to this histogram when a download warning was

shown in the download bubble, a notification, or the obsolete download

shelf. Given that the download bubble is suppressed for 15s after it is

shown, it is possible for a dangerous download warning to occur but not

be shown in the download bubble. Later on, the user could go to

chrome://downloads and be shown the warning, but this wouldn't be logged

to the histogram. This causes the histogram count to be lower than the

actual number of warnings shown to the user.



This CL fixes that by logging from chrome://downloads as well. We ensure

that each warning is only logged once by checking and setting the

WasUIWarningShown bit on the DownloadItemModel.



Since the missing warnings from chrome://downloads are expected to be

a low number, we do not change the name of the histogram. This histogram

is particularly costly to rename because it contains many years of

historical data and is used to populate internal dashboards.



Also some drive-by fixes.

entry.title: Pull //content/browser/renderer_host/input/input_router.h to
entry.content:
//content/common/input



This change also pulls mouse_wheel_event_queue, timeout_monitor,

touch_timeout_handler, touch_action_filter, input_router_client,

input_router_config_helper, passthrough_touch_event_queue from

//content/browser/renderer_host/input to //content/common/input since

these are dependencies of input_router.h. This refactoring is a part of

bigger project to handle input on viz thread (go/input-on-viz). We are

moving input related interfaces that RenderWidgetHostImpl uses to

//content/common/input. This would provide a single stack in

//content/common/input that we quickly enter in either the browser or

GPU viz which would allow for relatively clean movement of code. GPU

process can link in the same input stack and forward the data to the

renderer using the same code.
